content.text: ElizaOS has received a major update, introducing persistent memory and picture-generating abilities for ElizaOS, along with various website improvements.
Several dependencies have been updated, including SQLite, Tailwind Merge, Supabase, and ESLint, ensuring improved performance and security.
The environment has been updated with Twitter quality-of-life improvements, enhancing user experience.
New model providers, Bailian and Volengine, have been added to ElizaOS, expanding its AI capabilities.
The viem dependency has been updated to support the Arthera EVM chain, ensuring compatibility with newer blockchain technologies.
New language support has been added to the documentation, including Arabic and Hungarian translations.

The Eliza project continues to gain traction, reaching 7.9k stars on GitHub (+2.2k from last week), 2.1k forks (+400), and 237 contributors (+44). It is currently the #1 trending monthly GitHub repository.

Several updates and merges were made to the Eliza repository, including improvements to Twitter responses, updates to ESLint and formatting, and enhancements to testing frameworks. Other updates include SQLite-related changes, TypeScript improvements, and dependency upgrades such as clsx and uuid.
A new community section has been created, featuring cleaned-up documentation, a dedicated tab for community discussions, and a page for GitHub contributors.

A proposal has been made to introduce GitHub badges for community contributions, recognizing achievements such as first PR, first review, bug fixes, and enhancements. This aims to encourage participation and foster a stronger community.

ElizaOS now supports 45 plugins, including 18+ blockchain-related plugins. Client plugins include Discord, Telegram, Farcaster, WhatsApp, Twitter, and Slack. Blockchain plugins support Solana and all EVM chains.

Recent project updates from the WDYGDTW weekly meeting on 29/12 include Hyperfy.io integration, Eliza instance efficiency improvements, agentic JS documentation generation, an auto-documentation plugin, and a security auditing feature.
A recent pull request integrated Jin's documentation changes and rebuilt the documentation with a16z.

The GOAT plugin has been integrated into ElizaOS, enabling AI agents to interact with on-chain applications. This includes minting NFTs on Zora, swapping tokens on Uniswap, and placing bets on Polymarket with minimal code.
ElizaOS now supports running with Gitpod, simplifying the development environment setup.
Two new model providers, Ali Bailian (Qwen) and Volengine (Doubao, Bytedance), have been added to ElizaOS. These providers expand the available AI models for developers.
DeepSeek API has been integrated into ElizaOS, allowing access to the DeepSeek V3 model with 671B MoE parameters and 37B activated parameters.
A $5k bounty has been announced for integrating Twilio voice and text support into ElizaOS. This includes Deepgram or Whisper for speech-to-text and Elevenlabs for text-to-speech.
A work-in-progress feature integrates ElevenLabs for Twilio call handling, allowing ElizaOS agents to receive calls via Twilio.

The cryptocurrency market has seen fluctuations in the prices of major assets. Wrapped Bitcoin (WBTC) increased from $93,210.11 to $94,207.76. Wrapped Ethereum (WETH) also saw a rise from $3,332.45 to $3,353.25. Solana (SOL) moved up from $188.93 to $193.88. Additionally, ai16z experienced a significant increase from $1.59 to $2.19.

categories.title: Recent Bug Fixes and Issues in ElizaOS

content.text: The EVM Plugin actions are not functioning as expected. The issue arises because the code assumes that the options object passed to the handler contains all parsed parameters, which is not the case. Attempts to transfer ETH using the plugin result in a TypeError due to missing properties. The agent fails when trying to execute a transaction.

A bug in the message completion footer format was causing invalid JSON to be passed to the LLM, leading to frequent JSON parse errors inside an infinite loop. This resulted in excessive consumption of model provider credits. The issue has been fixed, reducing the risk of such errors.

A bug in the fact evaluator of the plugin-bootstrap module was identified where `{{user1}}` was mistakenly used instead of `{{user2}}` in the examples template. This issue has been corrected to ensure proper user attribution in conversations.
The image upload path in the DESCRIBE_IMAGE action was incorrect, causing issues when uploading images from the client. This has been fixed to ensure proper image handling.
Dependencies for the plugin-evm were not correctly set up, preventing it from building. This issue has been resolved, allowing the plugin to compile successfully.

Users attempting to set up ElizaOS with OpenAI as the model provider encountered an error stating that the `gpt-4o` model does not exist or is inaccessible. This issue prevents the agent from responding correctly.

An extra semicolon in the Supabase schema caused a syntax error when uploading the schema via the SQL editor. This issue has been fixed, allowing users to set up their Supabase database without errors.

categories.title: Improvements to Twitter Post Generation and Formatting

content.text: Enhancements have been made to improve Twitter response prompts and post content quality. These changes aim to reduce duplication in generated tweets and optimize token usage. The improvements include removing previous posts from the generation prompt to prevent repetition and refining the prompt structure for better organization and response quality.

A fix has been implemented to ensure tweets follow the correct formatting guidelines by enforcing double line breaks between statements. This improves readability and aligns with the intended prompt structure.

Multiple plugins in the project currently include duplicate dependencies, leading to version mismatches and bloated node_modules. This has caused issues, such as the recent problem with the 'viem' library in PR 1642.
To resolve this issue, shared dependencies should be moved to the root package.json file. This will ensure consistency across plugins, prevent version conflicts, and streamline dependency management.

Alternative approaches, such as manually managing dependencies within each plugin, have proven to be error-prone and unsustainable as the project scales. Consolidating dependencies at the root level will improve stability and simplify updates.
@shawmakesmagic highlights the importance of setting aside differences for the greater good of the community.
Multiple updates and merges have been made to the Eliza project, integrating changes from the main branch into various development branches.

categories.title: Integration of GaiaNet as a Decentralized GenAI Backend

content.text: A new decentralized GenAI backend has been added to Eliza, integrating GaiaNet as an alternative backend for large language models (LLMs). GaiaNet is a decentralized AI agent network that allows users to run GenAI models and proprietary knowledge bases on their own computers. It provides API services compatible with OpenAI, supporting LLM, voice-to-text, image-to-text, and text-to-voice models.

The integration allows Eliza to select Gaia nodes and domains as backend GenAI services. Users can configure their `.env` file to use GaiaNet by specifying model and server details. The change is considered low risk as it does not affect other functionalities. Documentation updates were made to reflect the new ModelProviderName.
A remote-tracking branch merge was performed to integrate the new backend feature into the main branch.
